{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537167"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:14:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15909"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15909"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.59,0.18,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8600"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103572"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8600","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8600"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85989"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"4981"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"11623"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34692"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103572"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice about migraine prevention. She has read about a recent study investigating the relationship between coffee consumption and migraine headaches. The study surveyed 1,000 adults at a single time point, collecting data about their coffee drinking habits and frequency of migraines over the past month. The researchers found that people who drank more than four cups of coffee per day were twice as likely to report migraines compared to those who drank less coffee.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this study design?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Case-control study","Cross-sectional study","Cohort study","Randomised controlled trial","Ecological study"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecross-sectional study\u003C/strong\u003E, which examines the relationship between an exposure (coffee consumption) and an outcome (migraines) at a single point in time. The key characteristic is that both the exposure and outcome are measured simultaneously through a survey at one time point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecase-control study\u003C/strong\u003E would start with people who have migraines (cases) and those who don\u0027t (controls), then look back at their coffee consumption. This differs from the current study where both variables were measured simultaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecohort study\u003C/strong\u003E would follow a group of people over time, perhaps starting with different levels of coffee consumption and tracking who develops migraines. This would allow for establishment of temporal sequence, which is not possible in the described study.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erandomised controlled trial\u003C/strong\u003E would involve randomly assigning participants to different levels of coffee consumption and measuring migraine outcomes. This would be an experimental rather than observational design.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eecological study\u003C/strong\u003E would examine the relationship between coffee consumption and migraines at a population level (e.g., comparing different countries or regions) rather than collecting individual-level data.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECross-sectional studies are useful for determining disease prevalence and generating hypotheses for future research. Their main limitation is the inability to establish temporal sequence and therefore causation. They are relatively quick and inexpensive to conduct but cannot determine whether exposure preceded outcome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cross-sectional studies measure exposure and outcome at a single point in time and cannot establish causation.","Cross-sectional studies are useful for determining disease prevalence and generating hypotheses for future research.","Selection bias and confounding are important limitations of cross-sectional studies."],"references":["Lu CY. Observational studies: a review of study designs, challenges and strategies to reduce confounding. Int J Clin Pract. 2009;63(5):691-697. doi:10.1111/j.1742-1241.2009.02056.x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85989"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15909"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85989"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T23:01:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-23T23:05:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8600"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103572"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag